In classic #rstats , functions are applied to objects by wrapping functions around the objects, using parentheses: function( object ) In the #tidyverse , functions are applied to objects by sending the objects to the function through a pipe, like this: object %>% function
All this is a long lead-up to what should have been a short reflection on the relationship between the way I traditionally did #rstats and the way I think of things in the #tidyverse

I respectfully disagree and think that it's a mistake to assume that kids can't grasp the underlying math and stats. I fundamentally believe that good content can teach these principles at age-appropriate levels of depth, and integrate with #rstats to foster understanding.

Doing analysis requires more prior knowledge in math & stats than entry-level programming. You could teach stats and code to kids but it’s a massive undertaking. It’s challenging even for postgrads/postdocs. You can do ANYTHING in #Rstats but it’s not always the best tool. #RLang
